<task id="AIPU2-030" project="Spaarke AI Platform Unification R2">
  <metadata>
    <title>Build SessionPersistenceService (Redis + Cosmos DB write-through)</title>
    <phase>2C</phase>
    <tags>bff-api, cosmos-db, redis, persistence</tags>
    <status>not-started</status>
    <estimated-effort>4 hours</estimated-effort>
    <dependencies>AIPU2-002, AIPU2-006</dependencies>
    <parallel-safe>false</parallel-safe>
  </metadata>
  <prompt>
    Build a SessionPersistenceService that implements a Redis + Cosmos DB write-through pattern
    for AI chat session storage. Every message must be durably persisted to both a hot tier
    (Redis, for fast session hydration) and a warm tier (Cosmos DB, for long-term compliance
    retention and cross-node availability). Cosmos DB write failures must be non-blocking —
    log the error and continue streaming rather than surfacing an error to the user. Redis
    write failures should be treated the same way. Partition Cosmos documents by tenantId
    to guarantee tenant isolation. Register the service via AddAiPersistenceModule so it is
    discoverable by the DI container.
  </prompt>
  <role>Senior .NET developer familiar with Cosmos DB SDK v3, Redis (StackExchange.Redis), and Azure AI streaming architectures.</role>
  <goal>
    Every chat message is persisted to both Redis (hot) and Cosmos DB (warm) within the request
    lifecycle. A write failure in either store is logged but never surfaces as a user-visible
    error or blocks the streaming response. The service is registered in DI and passes unit
    tests covering dual-write, hot-only fallback, and warm-only fallback scenarios.
  </goal>
  <knowledge>
    <files>
      <file>.claude/adr/ADR-009-redis-caching.md</file>
      <file>src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/Chat/ChatSessionManager.cs</file>
      <file>.claude/constraints/data.md</file>
    </files>
  </knowledge>
  <steps>
    <step>Read ChatSessionManager.cs to understand existing session model and message structure before designing the new service interface.</step>
    <step>Read ADR-009-redis-caching.md and data.md constraints to confirm allowed Redis usage patterns and Cosmos DB partitioning requirements.</step>
    <step>Create SessionPersistenceService.cs in src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/Persistence/. Define ISessionPersistenceService interface with PersistMessageAsync(sessionId, tenantId, message) and GetSessionAsync(sessionId, tenantId) methods.</step>
    <step>Implement dual-write logic: write to Redis first (hot tier, TTL = 24 hours), then write to Cosmos DB asynchronously (warm tier). Wrap each write in try/catch — on failure, log with ILogger at Warning level (include sessionId, tenantId, store name, exception) and continue. Do not re-throw.</step>
    <step>Configure Cosmos DB client using DefaultAzureCredential (no connection strings). Target the `sessions` container with partition key /tenantId. Use upsert semantics so resume/retry is idempotent.</step>
    <step>Configure Redis using the existing IConnectionMultiplexer registration (do not re-register). Key schema: sessions:{tenantId}:{sessionId}. Serialize with System.Text.Json.</step>
    <step>Create AddAiPersistenceModule(this IServiceCollection services) extension method in Infrastructure/DI/AiPersistenceModule.cs and register SessionPersistenceService as a scoped service. Call this from Program.cs.</step>
    <step>Write unit tests covering: (a) happy-path dual-write, (b) Redis failure — Cosmos still written, (c) Cosmos failure — Redis still written, (d) both fail — no exception thrown, only logs.</step>
  </steps>
  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion>PersistMessageAsync writes to Redis and Cosmos DB on every call in the normal path.</criterion>
    <criterion>A simulated Redis failure does not throw and does not prevent the Cosmos write.</criterion>
    <criterion>A simulated Cosmos failure does not throw and does not prevent the Redis write.</criterion>
    <criterion>Cosmos documents are partitioned by /tenantId (verified by inspecting the CosmosClient call in tests).</criterion>
    <criterion>DefaultAzureCredential is used for Cosmos authentication — no connection strings in code or config.</criterion>
    <criterion>Service is registered via AddAiPersistenceModule and resolves without error from the DI container.</criterion>
    <criterion>All unit tests pass (dotnet test).</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>
</task>
